==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sepulchre
<hw>Sep"ul*chre</hw> }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>sepulcre</ets>, OF. sepulcre, F.
<ets>s⟦eacute⟧pulcre</ets>, fr. L. <ets>sepulcrum</ets>,
<ets>sepulchrum</ets>, fr. <ets>sepelire</ets> to bury.]</ety> <def>The
place in which the dead body of a human being is interred, or a place
set apart for that purpose; a grave; a tomb.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The stony entrance of this <qex>sepulcher</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The first day of the week cometh Mary Magdalene early, when it was
yet dark, unto the <qex>sepulcher</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>John xx.
1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>A whited sepulcher</b></col>. <cd>Fig.: Any person who is
fair outwardly but unclean or vile within. See <au>Matt. xxiii.
27.</au></cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sepulchre</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Sepulcher</ent>⟦br⟧
<mhw>{

